'''HMCS ''Trinity''''' ([[Hull classification symbol (Canada)|hull number]] MCB 157) was a {{sclass2-|Bay|minesweeper}} that was constructed for the [[Royal Canadian Navy]] during the [[Cold War]]. Entering service in 1954, the minesweeper was [[Ship decommissioning|paid off]] in 1958 and transferred to the [[Turkish Navy]]. Renamed ''Terme'', the ship remained in service until 1991.

==Design and description==
The Bay class were designed and ordered as replacements for the [[Second World War]]-era minesweepers that the Royal Canadian Navy operated at the time. Similar to the {{sclass2-|Ton|minesweeper|1}}, they were constructed of wood planking and aluminum framing.<ref name=m1>Macpherson and Barrie, p. 271</ref><ref name=con1>Gardiner and Chumbley, p. 49</ref>

[[Displacement (ship)|Displacing]] {{convert|390|LT|t}} standard at {{convert|412|LT|t}} at deep load, the minesweepers were {{convert|152|ft|m|abbr=on}} [[Length overall|long]] with a [[Beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{convert|28|ft|m|abbr=on}} and a [[Draft (hull)|draught]] of {{convert|8|ft|m|abbr=on}}.<ref name=m1/><ref name=con1/> They had a complement of 38 officers and ratings.<ref name=m1/><ref group=note>Gardiner and Chumbley claim the complement was 40.</ref>

The Bay-class minesweepers were powered by two [[General Motors|GM]] 12-cylinder [[diesel engine]]s driving two shafts creating {{convert|2400|bhp|lk=in}}. This gave the ships a maximum speed of {{convert|16|kn|lk=in}} and a range of {{convert|3290|nmi|lk=in}} at {{convert|12|kn}}.<ref name=con1/><ref name=j1>Moore, p. 82</ref> The ships were armed with one [[40 mm Bofors]] gun and were equipped with minesweeping gear.<ref name=m1/><ref name=con1/>

==Operational history==
The ship's [[keel]] was laid down on 31 January 1952 by [[Davie Shipbuilding|George T. Davie & Sons. Ltd]] at their yard in [[Lauzon, Quebec|Lauzon]], [[Quebec]]. Named for a [[Trinity Bay, Newfoundland and Labrador|bay]] located in [[Newfoundland (island)|Newfoundland]], ''Trinity'' was [[Ship naming and launching|launched]] on 31 July 1953. The ship was [[Ship commissioning|commissioned]] on 16 June 1954.<ref name=mac277>Macpherson and Barrie, p. 277</ref>  The ship joined the [[First Canadian Minesweeping Squadron]] upon commissioning.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Three 'Sweepers Commissioned |magazine=The Crowsnest |location=Ottawa |publisher=Queen's Printer |date=August 1954 |number=6 |volume=10 |pages=3}}</ref> The squadron sailed to the Caribbean Sea in April 1955 for a training cruise, making several port visits.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Sweepers on W. Indies Cruise |magazine=The Crowsnest |location=Ottawa |publisher=Queen's Printer |volume=7 |number=6 |date=April 1955 |pages=2}}</ref> In May 1956, the First Canadian Minesweeping Squadron deployed as part of the [[NATO]] minesweeping exercise Minex Sweep Clear One in the western Atlantic.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=First Canadian Minesweeper Squadron |magazine=The Crowsnest |publisher=Queen's Printer |location=Ottawa |date=August 1956 |volume=8 |number=10 |pages=18}}</ref>

The ship remained in service with the Royal Canadian Navy until being [[Ship decommissioning|paid off]] on 21 August 1957.<ref name=mac277/> The ship was transferred to the [[Turkish Navy]] as part of the [[NATO]] [[Mutual Defense Assistance Act#Mutual Assistance Program - Military Assistance Program|Mutual Aid Agreement]] on 31 March 1958.<ref name=mac277/><ref>Milner, p. 220</ref> Renamed ''Terme'' by the Turkish Navy, the vessel sailed for Turkey on 19 May 1958.<ref>Moore, p. 462</ref> The ship remained in service until 1991.<ref>Colledge, p. 643</ref>

